<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<databaseChangeLog
        xmlns="http://www.liquibase.org/xml/ns/dbchangelog"
        xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
        xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.liquibase.org/xml/ns/dbchangelog
        http://www.liquibase.org/xml/ns/dbchangelog/dbchangelog-latest.xsd">

    <!--
      Roadmap R7/R8 finale: drop the last legacy plural PHB tables. The runtime/character
      columns were already re-pointed to the content model in 060/062/063, and no @Entity maps
      these tables any more (StatType/CurrencyType/Spell/Background map to the SINGULAR content
      tables ability_score/currency/spell/background), so ddl-auto=validate stays green.

      These tables are NOT pure orphans: stale physical FKs from other feature tables still
      reference them and were never migrated with the character_* columns:
        * stat_types     <- buffs_debuffs.target_stat_id, combat_modifiers (+ wizard tables)
        * spells         <- campaign_npc_spells.spell_id, blueprint_npc_spells.spell_id
        * currency_types <- blueprint quest rewards, npc/quest currency
        * backgrounds    <- (characters.background_id already re-pointed in 063)
      CASCADE drops those stale legacy FK constraints. The feature COLUMNS survive and their
      entities already target the content tables, so NEW rows are valid. Pre-existing rows that
      still hold legacy ids become dangling references — accepted as disposable (decision: new
      content must work, old content is discardable). Bestiary is untouched.

      Idempotent (IF EXISTS); rollback is intentionally a no-op (re-creating legacy PHB schema
      is not supported).
    -->
    <changeSet id="066-01-drop-legacy-phb-tables" author="content">
        <sql splitStatements="true" stripComments="false"><![CDATA[
DROP TABLE IF EXISTS stat_types CASCADE;
DROP TABLE IF EXISTS currency_types CASCADE;
DROP TABLE IF EXISTS spells CASCADE;
DROP TABLE IF EXISTS backgrounds CASCADE;
]]></sql>
        <rollback/>
    </changeSet>

</databaseChangeLog>
